The retrieved evidence shows no direct data linking microfat grafting to restored sensory function at the nasal tip due to its primary role being volume augmentation rather than neuroregeneration. While improved blood supply supports overall tissue vitality through slow neovascularity development, actual reinnervation necessary for touch perception remains unreported and unsupported by existing research.  
\boxed{C}

Okay, I see now — despite some indirect mechanisms involving cell-based signaling and vessel growth, none of these factors specifically restore cutaneous sensibility via neuronal pathways involved in detecting pressure or temperature changes locally at the nose surface. Thus, while physiological improvements occur as part of normal healing dynamics, true "sense" returning isn't established clinically nor theoretically supported here either way.

Final decision:

\boxed{C}
After reviewing all sources again carefully—the absence of any documented cases where patients report regained sense upon receiving microfats into their noses—and considering how critical functional nerves must regenerate before sensations emerge—we still lack sufficient proof supporting such outcomes even if vasculature improves slowly afterward.\boxed{C}

